<DOC><DOCNO> AP890830-0130 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-89 1815EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Philippines-Hostages     08-30 0202</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Philippines-Hostages,0208</SECOND><HEAD>Officer in Hostage Crisis Relieved of Command</HEAD><DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A Philippine Constabulary officer wasrelieved of his command two weeks after he led an assault to freehostages held by inmates in a siege in which 21 people died, themilitary announced Wednesday.   Legislators have criticized the military's handling of the crisisin Davao City.   However, Wilfred Garcia, the constabulary spokesman in DavaoCity, gave no reason for the transfer of Capt. Poblio Gildo andrefused to say if it was connected to the hostage crisis.   Gildo led the assault to end a three-day crisis when anAustralian missionary and 15 other people were held hostage by 16prisoners.   All the prisoners and five hostages, including the missionary,were killed before troops regained control of the jail, 610 milessoutheast of Manila.   Gildo was reassigned to the regional constabulary headquarters inDavao but was not immediately given specific duties, Garcia said.Gildo was succeeded by his deputy as commander of Davao City's 431stPhilippines Constabulary Company.   Australian officials have said the missionary's wounds indicatedshe may have been slain by government snipers who opened fire duringan abortive jailbreak a few hours before the prison was stormed.</TEXT></DOC>